{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"So the question is, what is invisible?"},{"time":5000,"text":"There is more of it than you think, actually."},{"time":8000,"text":"Everything, I would say. Everything that matters"},{"time":11000,"text":"except every thing and except matter."}]},{"cues":[{"time":17000,"text":"We can see matter. But we can't see what's the matter."},{"time":21000,"text":"As in this cryptic sentence I found in The Guardian recently:"},{"time":26000,"text":"\"The marriage suffered a setback in 1965,"},{"time":29000,"text":"when the husband was killed by the wife.\""},{"time":32000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":35000,"text":"There's a world of invisibility there, isn't there?"},{"time":37000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":39000,"text":"So, we can see the stars and the planets,"},{"time":41000,"text":"but we can't see what holds them apart"},{"time":44000,"text":"or what draws them together."},{"time":46000,"text":"With matter, as with people, we see only the skin of things."},{"time":49000,"text":"We can't see into the engine room."},{"time":51000,"text":"We can't see what makes people tick, at least not without difficulty."},{"time":54000,"text":"And the closer we look at anything, the more it disappears."},{"time":58000,"text":"In fact, if you look really closely at stuff,"},{"time":60000,"text":"if you look at the basic substructure of matter,"},{"time":62000,"text":"there isn't anything there."},{"time":64000,"text":"Electrons disappear in a kind of fuzz,"},{"time":66000,"text":"and there is only energy. And you can't see energy."}]},{"cues":[{"time":71000,"text":"So everything that matters, that's important, is invisible."},{"time":74000,"text":"One slightly silly thing that's invisible"},{"time":77000,"text":"is this story, which is invisible to you."},{"time":79000,"text":"And I'm now going to make it visible to you in your minds."},{"time":82000,"text":"It's about an M.P. called Geoffrey Dickens."}]},{"cues":[{"time":86000,"text":"The late Geoffrey Dickens, M.P. was attending a fete in his constituency."},{"time":89000,"text":"Wherever he went, at every stall he stopped he was closely followed"},{"time":92000,"text":"by a devoted smiling woman of indescribable ugliness."},{"time":95000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":97000,"text":"Try as he might, he couldn't get away from her."},{"time":99000,"text":"A few days later he received a letter from a constituent"},{"time":101000,"text":"saying how much she admired him,"},{"time":103000,"text":"had met him at a fete and asking for a signed photograph."},{"time":106000,"text":"After her name, written in brackets was the apt description, horse face."},{"time":111000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":112000,"text":"\"I've misjudged this women,\" thought Mr. Dickens."},{"time":114000,"text":"\"Not only is she aware of her physical repulsiveness,"},{"time":117000,"text":"she turns it to her advantage."},{"time":119000,"text":"A photo is not enough.\""},{"time":121000,"text":"So he went out and bought a plastic frame to put the photograph in."},{"time":124000,"text":"And on the photograph, he wrote with a flourish,"},{"time":126000,"text":"\"To Horse Face, with love from Geoffrey Dickens, M.P.\""},{"time":131000,"text":"After it had been sent off, his secretary said to him,"},{"time":133000,"text":"\"Did you get that letter from the woman at the fete?"},{"time":135000,"text":"I wrote Horse Face on her, so you'd remember who she was.\""},{"time":139000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":145000,"text":"I bet he thought he wished he was invisible, don't you?"},{"time":147000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":149000,"text":"So, one of the interesting things about invisibility"},{"time":151000,"text":"is that things that we can't see"},{"time":153000,"text":"we also can't understand."},{"time":155000,"text":"Gravity is one thing that we can't see"},{"time":157000,"text":"and which we don't understand."},{"time":159000,"text":"It's the least understood of all the four fundamental forces,"},{"time":161000,"text":"and the weakest."},{"time":163000,"text":"And nobody really knows what it is or why it's there."}]},{"cues":[{"time":165000,"text":"For what it's worth, Sir Isaac Newton, the greatest scientist who ever lived,"},{"time":168000,"text":"he thought Jesus came to Earth specifically to operate the levers of gravity."},{"time":173000,"text":"That's what he thought he was there for."},{"time":175000,"text":"So, bright guy, could be wrong on that one, I don't know."},{"time":178000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":180000,"text":"Consciousness. I see all your faces."},{"time":182000,"text":"I have no idea what any of you are thinking. Isn't that amazing?"},{"time":185000,"text":"Isn't that incredible that we can't read each other's minds?"},{"time":188000,"text":"But we can touch each other, taste each other perhaps, if we get close enough."},{"time":192000,"text":"But we can't read each other's minds. I find that quite astonishing."}]},{"cues":[{"time":195000,"text":"In the Sufi faith, this great Middle Eastern religion,"},{"time":199000,"text":"which some claim is the route of all religions,"},{"time":201000,"text":"Sufi masters are all telepaths, so they say."},{"time":206000,"text":"But their main exercise of telepathy"},{"time":208000,"text":"is to send out powerful signals to the rest of us that it doesn't exist."},{"time":213000,"text":"So that's why we don't think it exists,"},{"time":215000,"text":"the Sufi masters working on us."}]},{"cues":[{"time":218000,"text":"In the question of consciousness"},{"time":220000,"text":"and artificial intelligence,"},{"time":222000,"text":"artificial intelligence has really, like the study of consciousness,"},{"time":224000,"text":"gotten nowhere. We have no idea how consciousness works."},{"time":227000,"text":"With artificial intelligence, not only have they not created artificial intelligence,"},{"time":231000,"text":"they haven't yet created artificial stupidity."},{"time":234000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":239000,"text":"The laws of physics: invisible, eternal, omnipresent, all-powerful."},{"time":243000,"text":"Remind you of anyone?"},{"time":245000,"text":"Interesting. I'm, as you can guess,"},{"time":247000,"text":"not a materialist, I'm an immaterialist."},{"time":249000,"text":"And I've found a very useful new word, ignostic. Okay?"},{"time":252000,"text":"I'm an ignostic."},{"time":254000,"text":"I refuse to be drawn on the question of whether God exists,"},{"time":257000,"text":"until somebody properly defines the terms."},{"time":260000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":263000,"text":"Another thing we can't see is the human genome."},{"time":266000,"text":"And this is increasingly peculiar,"},{"time":269000,"text":"because about 20 years ago, when they started delving into the genome,"},{"time":274000,"text":"they thought it would probably contain around 100,000 genes."},{"time":277000,"text":"Geneticists will know this, but every year since,"},{"time":279000,"text":"it's been revised downwards."},{"time":281000,"text":"We now think there are likely to be only just over 20,000"},{"time":284000,"text":"genes in the human genome."}]},{"cues":[{"time":286000,"text":"This is extraordinary. Because rice -- get this --"},{"time":289000,"text":"rice is known to have 38 thousand genes."},{"time":293000,"text":"Potatoes, potatoes have 48 chromosomes. Do you know that?"},{"time":298000,"text":"Two more than people,"},{"time":300000,"text":"and the same as a gorilla."},{"time":302000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":304000,"text":"You can't see these things, but they are very strange."},{"time":307000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":309000,"text":"The stars by day. I always think that's fascinating."},{"time":312000,"text":"The universe disappears."},{"time":314000,"text":"The more light there is, the less you can see."}]},{"cues":[{"time":317000,"text":"Time, nobody can see time."},{"time":319000,"text":"I don't know if you know this. Modern physics,"},{"time":321000,"text":"there is a big movement in modern physics"},{"time":323000,"text":"to decide that time doesn't really exist,"},{"time":325000,"text":"because it's too inconvenient for the figures."},{"time":328000,"text":"It's much easier if it's not really there."},{"time":330000,"text":"You can't see the future, obviously."},{"time":332000,"text":"And you can't see the past, except in your memory."}]},{"cues":[{"time":335000,"text":"One of the interesting things about the past is"},{"time":337000,"text":"you particularly can't see. My son asked me this the other day,"},{"time":340000,"text":"he said, \"Dad, can you remember what I was like when I was two?\""},{"time":342000,"text":"And I said, \"Yes.\" And he said, \"Why can't I?\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":345000,"text":"Isn't that extraordinary? You cannot remember"},{"time":347000,"text":"what happened to you earlier than the age of two or three,"},{"time":350000,"text":"which is great news for psychoanalysts,"},{"time":352000,"text":"because otherwise they'd be out of a job."},{"time":354000,"text":"Because that's where all the stuff happens"},{"time":357000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":359000,"text":"that makes you who you are."}]},{"cues":[{"time":362000,"text":"Another thing you can't see is the grid on which we hang."},{"time":365000,"text":"This is fascinating. You probably know, some of you,"},{"time":368000,"text":"that cells are continually renewed. You can see it in skin and this kind of stuff."},{"time":371000,"text":"Skin flakes off, hairs grow, nails, that kind of stuff."},{"time":375000,"text":"But every cell in your body is replaced at some point."},{"time":378000,"text":"Taste buds, every 10 days or so."},{"time":380000,"text":"Livers and internal organs sort of take a bit longer. A spine takes several years."},{"time":384000,"text":"But at the end of seven years, not one cell in your body"},{"time":388000,"text":"remains from what was there seven years ago."},{"time":391000,"text":"The question is, who, then, are we?"},{"time":393000,"text":"What are we? What is this thing that we hang on,"},{"time":396000,"text":"that is actually us?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":400000,"text":"Okay. Atoms, you can't see them."},{"time":402000,"text":"Nobody ever will. They're smaller than the wavelength of light."},{"time":405000,"text":"Gas, you can't see that."},{"time":407000,"text":"Interesting. Somebody mentioned 1600 recently."},{"time":409000,"text":"Gas was invented in 1600"},{"time":411000,"text":"by a Dutch chemist called Van Helmont."},{"time":414000,"text":"It's said to be the most successful ever invention"},{"time":417000,"text":"of a word by a known individual."},{"time":419000,"text":"Quite good. He also invented a word called \"blas,\""},{"time":422000,"text":"meaning astral radiation."},{"time":424000,"text":"Didn't catch on, unfortunately."},{"time":426000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":428000,"text":"But well done, him."},{"time":430000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":431000,"text":"There is so many things that -- Light."},{"time":434000,"text":"You can't see light. When it's dark, in a vacuum,"},{"time":437000,"text":"if a person shines a beam of light straight across your eyes,"},{"time":440000,"text":"you won't see it. Slightly technical, some physicists will disagree with this."},{"time":443000,"text":"But it's odd that you can't see the beam of light,"},{"time":445000,"text":"you can only see what it hits."},{"time":447000,"text":"I find that extraordinary, not to be able to see light,"},{"time":449000,"text":"not to be able to see darkness."}]},{"cues":[{"time":451000,"text":"Electricity, you can't see that."},{"time":453000,"text":"Don't let anyone tell you they understand electricity."},{"time":455000,"text":"They don't. Nobody knows what it is."},{"time":457000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":458000,"text":"You probably think the electrons in an electric wire"},{"time":460000,"text":"move instantaneously down a wire, don't you, at the speed of light"},{"time":463000,"text":"when you turn the light on. They don't."},{"time":465000,"text":"Electrons bumble down the wire,"},{"time":467000,"text":"about the speed of spreading honey, they say."},{"time":470000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":472000,"text":"Galaxies, 100 billion of them estimated in the universe."},{"time":475000,"text":"100 billion. How many can we see? Five."},{"time":478000,"text":"Five out of the 100 billion galaxies, with the naked eye,"},{"time":481000,"text":"and one of them is quite difficult to see unless you've got very good eyesight."}]},{"cues":[{"time":485000,"text":"Radio waves. There's another thing."},{"time":487000,"text":"Heinrich Hertz, when he discovered radio waves in 1887,"},{"time":490000,"text":"he called them radio waves because they radiated."},{"time":492000,"text":"And somebody said to him,"},{"time":495000,"text":"\"Well what's the point of these, Heinrich?"},{"time":497000,"text":"What's the point of these radio waves that you've found?\""},{"time":500000,"text":"And he said, \"Well, I've no idea."},{"time":502000,"text":"But I guess somebody will find a use for them someday.\""},{"time":505000,"text":"And that's what they do, radio. That's what they discovered."}]},{"cues":[{"time":509000,"text":"Anyway, so the biggest thing"},{"time":512000,"text":"that's invisible to us is what we don't know."},{"time":514000,"text":"It is incredible how little we know."},{"time":517000,"text":"Thomas Edison once said,"},{"time":519000,"text":"\"We don't know one percent of one millionth"},{"time":521000,"text":"about anything.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":523000,"text":"And I've come to the conclusion --"},{"time":526000,"text":"because you've asked this other question, \"What's another thing you can't see?\""},{"time":529000,"text":"The point, most of us. What's the point?"},{"time":532000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":535000,"text":"(Applause)"},{"time":536000,"text":"You can't see a point. It's by definition dimensionless,"},{"time":539000,"text":"like an electron, oddly enough."}]},{"cues":[{"time":542000,"text":"But the point, what I've got it down to,"},{"time":545000,"text":"is there are only two questions really worth asking."},{"time":547000,"text":"\"Why are we here?\" and \"What should we do about it while we are?"},{"time":552000,"text":"And to help you, I've got two things to leave you with, from two great philosophers,"},{"time":557000,"text":"perhaps two of the greatest philosopher thinkers of the 20th century,"},{"time":560000,"text":"one a mathematician and an engineer, and the other a poet."}]},{"cues":[{"time":563000,"text":"The first is Ludwig Wittgenstein who said,"},{"time":567000,"text":"\"I don't know why we are here."},{"time":569000,"text":"But I'm pretty sure it's not in order to enjoy ourselves.\""},{"time":572000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":578000,"text":"He was a cheerful bastard wasn't he?"},{"time":580000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":583000,"text":"And secondly and lastly, W.H. Auden,"},{"time":585000,"text":"one of my favorite poets, who said,"},{"time":587000,"text":"\"We are here on earth"},{"time":590000,"text":"to help others."},{"time":592000,"text":"What the others are here for, I've no idea.\""},{"time":595000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":597000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}